<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="...328fedb22570524062aeb1303" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Ophidian 2350</option><option value='/magic/treports/treports.php'>The Wastelands</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Nazgul and Realms of the Elf Lords<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.43)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=10558'>Ulaire "Morgul Minas" Lemenya</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=10558&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> July 8, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Controversial Introduction<br />
Hi there it is time to have another look at the Nazgul and see how they have fared in this latest expansion. I have heard people say they have done very badly in this expansion, some say even worse than Moria! I doubt that as their cards are utterly worthless except for Such a Little Thing and there are MANY cards that hurt them. While Nazgul have not received the boost that the Uruk-Hai have I believe there are still some useful cards for them in this set and overall they haven’t done too badly.<br />
<br />
How can I say that you ask? They only had 6 cards in the set whereas Sauron got a whopping 19! First you have to look at more than just number. Half the Sauron cards are worthless discard cards and most of the others are weak and pointless minions. I doubt more than about half a dozen of the cards will ever be used except in bizarre decks or discard decks. The Orc Pillager is good enough to win some battles, the Orc Swordsman is fantastic if you play with weapons, Our List of Allies Grows Thin could be useful and Terrible as The Dawn would be great except that Sauron is already the best equipped culture to deal with Galadriel due to their Tower Assassins. I am sure someone will tell me something like His Cruelty and Malice or Tower of Barad-Dur is broken but I will believe it when I see it beat me in a game. The other playable card could be Gleaming in the Snow which I will talk about later. So really Sauron have not done that well.<br />
<br />
Isengard on the other hand have done very, very well in this expansion. Not only did they get an entire new sub-culture but they got some huge boosts to their already very strong Uruk-Hai. Saruman is one of the best cards in the set, Abandoning Reason for Madness looks very handy, the Isengard Smith is one of those rare minions like the Tower Assassin, Enquea or Nelya that can fit into almost any deck. One of You Must Do This looks tempting, the Orthanc Berserker will be a horror due to the new Saruman, The Palantir of Orthanc has already annoyed me a couple of times, the Tower of Orthanc is very strong and the Uruk Ravager will see play in decks that use a lot of Saruman. Ok, there is no way the Ringwraiths can compare with that but as you will see they have gained a bit.<br />
<br />
<br />
Cards that Hurt<br />
Before I look at the actual cards that the Nazgul did get lets have a look at what they didn’t get. By this I mean what things were introduced that hurt them. For example the biggest problem since Mines of Moria has been those evil cost 0 Flaming Brands. Was there anything devastating like that to come out of this set?<br />
I would say no in general however there are (naturally) some annoying cards.<br />
<br />
Galadriel allows them to probably duck the Ford unless you have Nelya. Losing your most important site is always very bad news.<br />
<br />
Galdor is evil. You played the Witch King with Pale Blade on the Black Steed and this twit sends him back to your hand for one exerting. Argh! Their Power is in Terror is looking like it might be very handy for more than stopping Mirror decks and exhausting Bounder. Galdor hurts.<br />
<br />
Vilya will get rid of that crucial Blade tip or Black Breath which is annoying but at least it isn’t discarded.<br />
<br />
Voice of Nimrodel could also be very bad news for our big black friends. I will have to wait and see if it is played much but it looks useful, a Get Out of Jail Free card for Elves. I would consider putting one into an Elf deck.<br />
<br />
Narya could stop your Burden deck corrupting the Ring Bearer, but it is very expensive to use and those extra twilight could turn into some nasty minions that kill him instead.<br />
<br />
Aragorn will choke us which as every Nazgul player knows is very bad news. Once again we will have to wait and see if this version is played much. While it is good I think it is only the third best Aragorn but I am sure others will disagree.<br />
<br />
The Shards of Narsil will be horrible. This one card will tip the entire game yet a bit more towards the fellowship. I hope a shadow version is forthcoming. This hurts all shadow cultures, hard to say which one will suffer the most but it could be Nazgul. It would be even worse except that there has recently been a very good rule change to ARV which I will discuss later.<br />
<br />
Bill the Pony, did I already say the Nazgul hate choke decks?<br />
<br />
Melilot Brandybuck could hurt Burden decks except that I doubt she will see much play.<br />
<br />
The Shire Countryside will not see much play but occasionally you will might across a deck that has 4 and all sorts of wacky ways of adding and removing burdens so that they can heal everyone. I can’t say I will stay up late worrying about this but it would be fun to play against.<br />
<br />
House of Elrond removes a burden which is annoying but shouldn’t be that big as you WILL be going second so that they go to the Ford wont you?<br />
<br />
<br />
The Witch King says, “Nice rule changes”.<br />
There have been two major rule changes that came out at the same time as this set. (Yes I know this doesn’t really belong here but I wanted to say how great these changes are for Nazgul.)  <br />
<br />
ARV the most broken card in the game has been made only fantastic. Exhaust any one Minion for one exertion is still great but at least now they (probably) will have to fight Cantea or The Witch King.<br />
<br />
Thror’s Map now is hard to use and one use. Once again it is still a good card but not an automatic choice for every deck that was ever made. This protects your crucial sites like whichever site 2 you use, the Ford of Bruinen and Anduin Wilderland. <br />
<br />
These are two great improvements to the game as far as Nazgul are concerned. If I put on my fellowship hat I may disagree.<br />
<br />
<br />
Cards that Hurt Other Cultures<br />
Song of Durin will be hated by Moria. Dust off your Goblin Warriors boys and girls.<br />
<br />
Galdor will also annoy Lurtz, the Cave Troll and...ah...actually I can’t think oeasterlingood Sauron minion once the Tower Assassin is exhausted, but Galdor will get rid of whichever one will be the least bad.<br />
<br />
Long Knives of Legolas are this sets revenge for Flaming Brand. These hurt everyone else and I think they will see a lot of play.<br />
<br />
The Shards of Narsil will be horrible for everyone.<br />
<br />
Frying Pan could be useful, while I doubt it will replace Sting as a second or third weapon it has the ability to really hurt some Orcs.<br />
<br />
Caras Galadhon really hurts Moria and will allow much safer double moves from site 5 if players have some way to play their sites (such as a Pathfinder stacked under the Shards) or are coming second. Also a very annoying site for Sauron as they finally have the chance to swarm here but now they can’t. <br />
<br />
The Great River also hurts Moria a lot (have I said yet this set really kicked them). A slight inconvenience for Isengard (Captain) and Nazgul (Nertea) but nothing compared to Moria. <br />
<br />
My conclusion. Isengard has been greatly helped, Sauron has been hurt a little and Moria has taken some huge body blows. What about the Nazgul?<br />
<br />
<br />
The Nazgul Cards (Finally)<br />
Gates to the Dead City: gives a strong boost to burden decks, making every burden you add have both a long term and a short term impact. Imagine Blade Tip on Frodo and four of this out. Almost as good as Under the Watching Eye. I like it.<br />
<br />
News of Mordor: Has problems. Unless you add in the Uruk Scout to protect you from ARV (and the Orc Scout is slightly better so why would you?) why would you have an Uruk in a Nazgul deck? This card will not encourage me to play two cultures that don’t mix well. You might have a couple of Nazgul in an Isengard deck but you want your events playable easily not on rare occasions. If the card was something like Damage +2 I would be very excited and start looking at ways to mix them up but this is probably not enough. One new possibility is the Isengard Smith. <br />
<br />
The Ring Draws Them: this card draws me. I look at it and think it looks great. Then I think about all the things that could go wrong, I play it (cost 2!) and stupid Secret Sentinels get rid of it, Sam removes all of the burdens and I get nothing, Gandalf kills all of my conditions or I have a turn where I don’t draw a Nazgul (already a disaster!) and I put it down again and go looking for my 4th Morgul Gates.<br />
<br />
They Will Never Stop Hunting You: another borderline card. While the potential to protect yourself is great I can just see myself drawing their Dagger Strike or Savagery to Match Their Numbers. I am a little conservative and tend to go for cards that you can depend on, however I know a lot of people are not like that. They look at cards like this and see only the potential to exhaust Aragorn before the Archery phase. The card would have been better if it was played in the Shadow phase before ARV could be played. This card depends on your personality. If it works it is very strong benefit. Is it worth the risk?<br />
<br />
Too Great And Terrible: excellent. Nazgul really hate all of their Blade Tips and Black Breaths being wiped out by Gandalf. This is better than They Will Never Stop Hunting You because it wounds, not exerts the target. In this case it is good that this card is played in the Maneuver phase as they may have just used the card that would have saved Gandalf such as Wielder of the Flame, You Cannot Pass, Deep in Thought, Depart Silently or His First Serious Check. At worst you get rid of a couple of Servants of the Secret Fire, at best you kill Gandalf. If people in your area play Gandalf it is well worth the slot.<br />
<br />
Ulaire Otsea (correct spelling): A great addition to burden decks. Now you can really get the pain happening by putting that Blade Tip straight onto Frodo. The problem is that he won’t win many skirmishes by himself so you will need some helper cards – Black Steed, Nazgul Sword, Morgul Blade, Frozen by Fear or Threshold of Shadow. A great addition to the Twilight Nazgul arsenal who really needed a little more variety. The downside is that the Ostea (not Otsea) version was the one that made all those stupid non-fierce Twilight Nazgul fierce.<br />
<br />
Eregion Hills: Every burden helps. About time there was a site after 3 that really helped Nazgul. Will be very popular.<br />
<br />
Gates of Argonath: Fantastic news! Site seven they can’t shoot us and here they can’t ARV us. Protects from a whole host of other cards (just look at the Gandalf cards above for a start) as well. Probably THE Nazgul site 8.<br />
<br />
Get off The Road: Not a Nazgul card but you have to spot one as well as a Sauron minion to play it. Helps the fairly weak discard strategy. While more likely to be used in a Sauron deck that has a few Nazgul it could get rid of a lot of cards in a Twilight Nazgul Burden deck.  Still I am happy to leave my copies of this on the road until I see an effective discard deck.<br />
<br />
Gleaming in the Snow: Again not a Nazgul card but quite a few Nazgul decks do include either the Orc Scout, Tower Assassin or the Morgul Skulker so you can play it. Cost 0 is good, its just a matter of being able to exert the Orc in the regroup phase. The one thing that does protect them is that often your opponents big guns are up against your Nazgul leaving Frodo, Sam or Legolas to deal with the little Orcs. If you are seriously going to try and win by corruption and use some Sauron anyway it is worth a look.<br />
<br />
Isengard Smith: Still another card that is not a Nazgul. Ever wished you could get rid of those Flaming Brands? Aragorn’s Bow? Gwemegal? Your opponent refuses to fight Cantea with anyone with a weapon? Well here is the answer. Even better people often play five companions (not 6!) against Nazgul so it could be goodbye to all of their possessions. This can be such a scary prospect that they might risk an overwhelm in another skirmish to put someone with a damage bonus on the Smith.<br />
<br />
<br />
Carefully Considered Conclusion<br />
While Nazgul have not received any huge boosts like Isengard they are probably a bit stronger than before this set. Moria have been hurt a lot and Sauron a hurt a little. It is still too early to make the call on the Isengard Orcs. For the Nazgul the new sites are a great help and there are enough interesting and fun cards to let you tweak your Nazgul decks just a little bit.<br />
<br />
Now go and find the ring.<br />
